  "articleSummary": "**Summary:**  \nThe article argues that modern developer laptops have become “credential warehouses” – they store browser sessions, SSH keys, `.env` files, cloud‑CLI configs, token‑based auth, backups, and even crypto wallets – and a single compromised click can expose all of these assets. It outlines realistic threat vectors (phishing PDFs, malicious SMS links, poisoned ads, compromised npm packages, AI‑assistant misuse) and shows how infostealers like Lumma harvest local secrets to gain production‑level access, citing recent Microsoft and Mandiant incidents. The piece is written as a practical, cautionary analysis for developers, security engineers, and team leads, using the metaphor of a “desk drawer” full of keys to illustrate how easily attackers can turn a laptop breach into a full‑scale compromise.",
